text.tspan: 7.5.1OIL SPILLAction to be taken by the vessel is given in Section 4 of the Emergency Contingency and Planning Manual and the vessel’s SOPEP /SMPEP.2) Prepare to dispatch a “task team” to the scene at short notice and make arrangement to man the office on 24 hrs basis by rotatingschedules.3) Notify the Owners, vessel’s PNI Club, H&M underwriters, local regulatory authorities, flag administration and classification society.4) Appoint an agent, if not already appointed, and establish contacts with the local clean-up contractors or cooperatives.5) Always assume that the coastline will be affected when large spill occurs and plan for the worst case situation when spillemergencies occur.6) At incident location, set up a “field office” and convene strategy and start-up planning meeting with On Scene Co-ordinator of thelocal authority, clean-up contractors, P & I representative.7) Notify the contact telephone, fax number of the “field office” to all appropriate parties including the vessel.8) Make arrangement for logistics support.9) Study the current and tidal variation of area to assess spill movement.10) Establish response priorities.11) To appoint a salvage company if considered necessary.12) After consultation with the local port authorities and on-scene coordinator, check possibility of shifting the vessel to a safeanchoring haven.13) If the incident necessities lightering of tanks, make arrangement with a lightering company for effecting emergency lighteringoperation.14) Request approval of appropriate government agencies before using dispersant, if appropriate.15) Notify government agencies of proposed activities.16) Establish close contact with the vessel, obtain status report and update them with actions being taken.17) Keep the senior management updated on a regular basis.18) On daily basis:hold meeting with government agencies to obtain agreement on acceptable levels of response and cleanup operationhold planning meeting with the cleanup contractors and other cooperatives.conduct site inspection to make sure objectives are being accomplished and accordingly evaluate and adjust response prioritiesmaintain a prepare log of events as per the format attached as Appendix 1maintain close liaision with the P&I representative and Classification surveyor, if required.19) Transmit updated status report for review and draft Press Release to senior management for their approval. Do not release anyinformation to the press unless formal approval has been obtained from the management and the vessel’s owner. If necessaryappoint a Media Management firm for guidance.20) Periodically authorise procurement of agreed equipment, manpower and services and approve invoices for payment.21) Make request for funds as deemed necessary.7.5.2GROUNDING AND STRANDINGAction to be taken by the vessel is given in Section 4 of the Emergency Contingency and Planning Manual.Main Engines not to be used prior complete assessment of the situation & express approval from the office.Tugs NOT to be taken / used without express approval of the office.Master to remain on complete command and NOT to be pressurized by the Pilots (if on board), if they insist on using the Main Engines or Tugs to refloat thevessel.2) Instruct vessel to monitor the sounding of all double bottom tanks and voids more frequently and to notify all changes in thesituation and conditions.3) Establish contact with the agents and make arrangement for tugs as necessary.4) Notify vessel’s owner, H&M underwriters, P&I Club in case of any P&I related matters like pollution, cargo damage, personnel injuryetc. Also charterers to be notified through the owner in case of charterer’s liability.5) Notify the vessel’s classification society and make arrangement for underwater hull inspection in coordination with H&Munderwriters and/or charterers (if applicable).6) In case of any damage to hull affecting seaworthiness of vessel make arrangement for suitable repair.7) Instruct the vessel staff to recheck the main engine crank webs deflection in the afloat condition and clean/flush the coolers in caseof silt/mud intake while aground.7.5.3COLLISION
